<br>
One key issue in warp drive theories is the notion of distance in space.<br>
<br>
The distance from Earth to Andromeda is assumed to be measured in a &quot;curved&quot; space. Basically, you imagine to fire a laser beam towards Andromeda, count the time it takes to go and return, and compute the distance assuming the standard constant value for the light speed for the whole travel. You get, let's say, 2MLY (2 MegaLightYears).<br>
<br>
The key point is that any measure of distance between two points in two different IRF is carried out using light. Light is the only thing that moves from one IRF to another, the observers remain steady in the origin of each IRF.<br>
<br>
The measure of the speed of light in an IRF assumes that the space &quot;moves together&quot; with the IRF. The two points (steady in the IRF) used to mark the distance L to be covered by the light beam are thus assumed to be origins of two IRF moving at the same speed, thus their relative speed is zero.<br>
<br>
Now, imagine that space moves independently of the IRF you measure the speed of light in. More precisely, imagine that the &quot;start&quot; mark is slower than the &quot;end&quot; mark, and that relative speed of the two marks is v. You can't perceive any &quot;growth&quot;, as it happens in 4 dimensions.<br>
<br>
Imagine also that photons are not affected by this growth, thus they &quot;see&quot; a relative motion of the two marks. When the light reaches the end mark, it has travelled for L + v T. But if you determine T using a clock placed at the end mark, then you have to correct the measure. The term beta in the Lorentz equations is indeed a beta(x, v), where x is unknown (you're measuring it).<br>
<br>
x = (L beta(x, v)+ v beta(x, v) T) beta(x, v)/T<br>
<br>
x = (L + v beta^2(x, v) T)/T<br>
<br>
Thus, the speed of light depends on the speed of expansion of the space-time, and can't be identical everywhere. Nevertheless, only photons can detect this phenomenon, as no object in a growing space can't detect the growth. Thus, any experiment carried out by an observer other than a photon shall say &quot;x = cost&quot;.<br>
<br>
If you assume that x = cost truly everywhere, then, to make your model match the reality (the one generated by the two hypotheses), you must &quot;correct&quot; the distance L from start mark to end mark so that:<br>
<br>
L' = (L + v beta^2(x, v) T).<br>
<br>
This means that to match the local values of x you must change the distance between two points depending on where they are in the space-time.<br>
<br>
Thus:<br>
L' = L + v beta^2(x, v) T.<br>
<br>
means that the space-time metric of distance is a function of space-time speed of expansion and of the measures of time (curved space-time).<br>
<br>
In any case, L(x, v, T) = L/T + v beta^2(x, v) means that a mass m travelling from start mark to end mark at constant speed L/T shall be actually subject to a net motion quantity change given by m v beta^2(x, v). According to Newton laws, this means that the mass m shall perceive a force. But as the measured speed is constant along the path start mark -&gt; end mark, this force can't have components in the direction of motion.<br>
<br>
Thus, any mass moving along a line along which v is not zero shall perceive a force normal to its motion (gravity force). Nevertheless, any mass moving along a line along which v is zero shall not perceive any gravity force. As a consequence, mass is not a source of gravity, it simply perceives it due to the space-time expansion.<br>
<br>
Again, if you move along a line along which v is negative, you perceive a &quot;negative&quot; (opposite direction) gravity. If you oscillate along a zero-gravity path in the space-time, then you are bound to it.<br>
<br>
A nice possibility of this theory is that the orbits of planets around the stars are zero-gravity paths, with other zero-gravity paths between them. Thus, in principle it is possible to compute a loop that uses zero-gravity paths to accelerate a mass only at given point in space. <br>
