<br>
1.) Dark matter does not have negative energy density. You're thinking exotic matter. Dark matter is made up of normal particles such as protons and neutrons. Exotic matter is not. Dark matter is just matter that does not give off enough energ for us to detect it. <br>
<br>
Oh, and there is plenty of evidence supporting the existence of dark matter. It's been a conjecture for the past decade.<br>
<br>
2.) The Alcubierre drive seems to be the only good candidate for interstellar travel. We will not get matter up to the speed of light and even traveling at relativistic velocities, it wouldn't be fast enough. Unfortunately, no one is doing any more work on the Alcubierre drive and even if so... we still have to find this so-called exotic matter and then find a way to implement it. <p>Rev. J. Vance Tyree<br>
